<br>
Here is the most blatant example I can think of as to why a reservation system is philosophically better than FCFS.  Lets say you have two guilds.  Guild A is like Reso or FnF.  Guild B is like my guild (Winds of Destiny) or perhaps an alliance of smaller guilds (i.e. the Fellowship).  Guild A has killed Trakanon countless times.  He is no longer a challenge to them.  Guild B has never killed Trakanon.  Most members have never even been to his lair.  Guild B (or the alliance they belong to), decide to go for Trakanon the next time the server comes up for a patch.  They post their intent on this board so hopefully no one else will go after Trak.  They plan this for days and everyone is excited about the possibility of doing something new in the game.  Patch day comes and everyone in Guild B gathers to start the raid.  However, their plans are dashed when they find out Guild A killed Trak less than an hour after the server came up with a group of 6 people.  The members of Guild B are disappointed and discouraged. <br>
<br>
A FCFS system is realistically better than a reservation system because you don't have to worry about the hassle of making a reservation system work.   <br>
<br>
I've been playing EQ since the week it was released so I've seen this issue discussed countless times.  Based on these countless discussions, here is what I can tell you about reservation versus FCFS.  FCFS is the preferred system for guilds that have a large roster of folks that play during primetime.  They are not necessarily a hard core raiding guild, but they can mobilize quickly if needed.  A reservation system is preferred by guilds with a lot of casual players.  They never have a consistent number of players on at primetime.  They have to schedule raids in advance so their members can fit it into their real life schedule.<br>
<br>
A reservation system could be used on FV, if the entire community was committed to making it work.  The problem is there is little incentive for the Top10 guilds to participate.  Without their support, a reservation system is doomed to fail. <p>Kebkin <!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><br>
